description: From the participle stem of Renaissance Latin effectuare, or its source, Latin effectus (“effect”); probably after Middle French effectuer.

verbs.description: effectuate (third-person singular simple present effectuates, present participle effectuating, simple past and past participle effectuated)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To cause, bring about (an event); to accomplish, to carry out (a wish, plan etc.). [from 16th c.]
